nal borders. Drawing on her own experience traveling across twenty countries within just over a year, Saraswati aims to bring readers along on her journey so that they might ask themselves, “How can I live with pain differently?”By using pain as a lens of feminist analysis, Scarred allows us to chart how power produces and operates through pain, and how pain is embodied and embedded in relationships. Saraswati provides a heartfelt and engaging recount of her experiences while also pushing the boundaries of the respective fields her story engages with. She allows for renewed academic and personal insights to blossom by using a blend of transnational feminist theory, travel studies, and pain studies. Ultimately, Scarred invites us to reframe pain and ask how might we carry it in a more humane, life-sustaining, enchanting, and feminist way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPainxPsychological aspects. 0aWomenxPsychology. 0aWomenxTravel. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075163540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479817115.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479817115423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479817115/original  a978-3-11-075163-5  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131926-1  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Eng